I found an ugly way to change the standard font.
Example to change the font size to 9 pt:

```
const StylesXform = require("exceljs/lib/xlsx/xform/style/styles-xform.js");
const origStylesXformInit = StylesXform.prototype.init;
StylesXform.prototype.init = function() {
   origStylesXformInit.apply(this, arguments);
   this._addFont({size: 9, color: {theme: 1}, name: 'Calibri', family: 2, scheme: 'minor'});
};

```

Here is a workaround if anyone is interested. This code is at the end of the routine (after all data and cell formats are configured). I only needed to default the font size and name, but you can expand on this to include other styles as well.

```javascript
workbook.eachSheet(sheet => {
  sheet.eachRow(row => {
    row.eachCell(cell => {
      // default styles
      if (!cell.font?.size) {
        cell.font = Object.assign(cell.font || {}, { size: 10 });
      }
      if (!cell.font?.name) {
        cell.font = Object.assign(cell.font || {}, { name: 'Arial' });
      }
    });
  });
});

@Will-at-FreedomDev's solution works. A `style` option for the `addWorksheet` function would make since.

```js
  const ws = wb.addWorksheet('My sheet', {
    style: {
      font: {
        size: 10,
        name: 'Arial'
      }
    }
  })
```

> @Will-at-FreedomDev's solution works. A `style` option for the `addWorksheet` function would make since.
> 
> ```js
>   const ws = wb.addWorksheet('My sheet', {
>     style: {
>       font: {
>         size: 10,
>         name: 'Arial'
>       }
>     }
>   })
> ```

Ability to customize default styling would be very useful like this.

I did the following workaround:

```
const addRow = (worksheet, row = []) => {
  const newRow = worksheet.addRow(row);
  newRow.font = {
    size: 10
  };

  return newRow;
}
```

find: `worksheet.addRow\((.*)\)`
replace: `addRow(worksheet,$1)`
